"{\"uid\": \"inews.co.uk-inews-lifestyle-money-saving-and-banking-splashed-5k-five-days-paris-fans-spending-olympics-3212141\", \"text\": \"IMPARTIAL NEWS + INTELLIGENT DEBATE  Account  Despite spending thousands on the events, attendees said it was worth the high price tag  This year, thousands flocked to Paris for the 2024 Olympics. And while some visitorsspared no expense in the French capital, others have gotten by on a very tight budget.  The event has already lived up to many people's expectations despite coming at ahuge costwith airfare, accommodation, metro, and restaurant prices through the roof - not to mention the cost of the tickets themselves.  But how much are Britons really paying to experience the Games in the City of Lights? We spoke to attendees to find out exactly how much their trip has set them back.  Two adults and one child, three events, three nights in Lille and two in Paris = \\u00a34,931.63  Alexandra Coutts, 35, her wife Amanda and their seven-year-old daughter Antonia splashed out to watch three sporting events - the men's artistic gymnastics, the women's canoe slalom semi-final and final in Paris, and the women's basketball preliminaries in Lille.  Speaking toi, the luxury travel specialist atScott Dunn, from Hove, said: \\\"Amanda and I agreed that we wanted to go to these Olympics in 2019 when we found the option of going to Tokyo 2020 prohibitively expensive.  \\\"I pre-registered to buy tickets and was given access in one of the later purchase windows, on 17 May 2023.  \\\"At that time, I bought the basketball tickets in Lille and the canoe slalom ones. Then, in November, further tickets were suddenly available, which is when we were able to secure the men's artistic gymnastics finals tickets. This was wonderful, but also incredibly annoying as I would never have bought the canoe slalom tickets if I had felt that I had better options, in my opinion.\\\"  The tickets set them back by \\u00a31,770.11 for the three of them - over a third of their overall spend.  The family arrived by Eurostar on Saturday 27 July, tickets which cost a total of \\u00a3321 with the Lille station fortunately only a short walk from their aparthotel in the city. Their one-bedroom apartment with a kitchen and washing machine cost \\u00a3809.  During their time in Lille, outside of watching the Games they enjoyed dinner out every day but one - when they cooked in the apartment - costing around \\u00a370 per meal. Light lunches and snacks on their way to the stadium cost around \\u00a325 per day. One day, as a treat while watching the basketball, the hotdogs, arancini and chips at the Stade Pierre-Mauroy cost \\u00a321 roughly.  The trio took a train from Lille to Paris on Tuesday 30 July, costing \\u00a3105.08, where they were staying for two more nights. Here, they stayed in a four-star hotel for \\u00a3714.  As they were just moments from the Eiffel Tower, one night they decided to take a trip to the top for a meal. All in, this cost \\u00a3125.12 including tickets for the lift, a pizza to share, drinks and some memorabilia.  On Thursday 1 August, it was finally time to make the journey back to the UK, via the Eurostar, which cost them \\u00a3256. Due to train cancellations, they ended up getting a taxi home from the station, adding another \\u00a390 to their already large bill.  However, Alexandra said: \\\"We are so glad we went. The cost did not detract from the experience at all.\\\"  One adult, two events and one night in Paris = \\u00a3419.73  However, others enjoyed the Games for much less. Rugby fan Deepak Tailor, from London, managed to bag an Airbnb for one night in the centre of Paris for just \\u00a348 - a bargain compared to the hefty prices many hotels are charging during the competition.  The founder of latestfreestuff.co.uk said: \\\"I travelled to Paris on Saturday 3 August on the Eurostar as I had tickets to watch the semi-finals and the final for the Rugby.  \\\"I was only there for about 24 hours because I found a cheap British Airways flight home the next day for \\u00a337, which was a lot less than the \\u00a3189 I paid for the Eurostar from London.\\\"  Deepak wanted to keep costs as low as possible, so kept meals very low-key. He spent \\u00a34.50 on breakfast on the Eurostar, \\u00a33.50 on a sandwich from M&S in King's Cross station which he ate for lunch, and \\u00a318 on dinner in a local French restaurant.  The only other times he dipped into his pocket was for a \\u00a31.50 bottle of water, a \\u00a31.81 trip on the Metro in Paris and \\u00a35.99, before the trip, on a few Fiji flags from Amazon.  He added: \\\"Despite the cost, everyone really loved it. My family grew up in Fiji, and the only medal that Fiji has ever won in their history at the Olympic Games was a medal in the rugby, so this was a once in a lifetime opportunity for us to watch them play live and win an Olympic medal.  \\\"The last time they won a medal at the Olympic Games they declared a public holiday in the country - that shows you how much it means to them. Now we are a part of that history.\\\"  Two adults, three events and seven nights in Paris = \\u00a33,670.50 (approximately)  Judith Annakie-Eriksen, 60, and her husband Jesper splashed out on what's called a 'Category A' package of tickets in February last year. This included access to the men's gymnastics qualifiers - \\u00a3112 each, the men's and women's archery - \\u00a343 each, and the women's volleyball prelims - \\u00a3103 each.  The couple spent \\u00a356 roughly to get from their house in Langdon Hills, Essex, to London St Pancras, before hopping on the Eurostar which they booked in November last year and cost them \\u00a3476 for a return ticket. They were two of the unlucky few who were caught up in the travel chaos on Friday July 26 - the day of the Opening Ceremony - so decided to get a \\u00a361 taxi from Gare du Nord to their hotel in Paris after their long day of travelling.  The ceramic artist and pottery tutor said: \\\"Our hotel was quite pricey - we paid \\u00a32,259 for seven nights in a standard double room at the Ibis Hotel. It was very small for two people but during our stay we left the hotel right after breakfast and usually returned late after dinner, by which time we were ready to sleep.  \\\"We ate out every day. Depending on what we were doing or how hungry we were, we had a light lunch and a larger evening meal in a restaurant. Our average spend was \\u00a3100 per day for two people on food, including alcohol - usually a couple of beers for my husband and a mocktail or a prosecco for me.  \\\"Other than that, we spent \\u00a315 per day on refreshments and \\u00a380 on merch. But for me, it was always a dream to visit an Olympic Games so I did not mind spending the money to ensure we enjoyed it.  \\\"The experience was well worth the money, in my opinion.\\\"  Impartial news + intelligent debate  All rights reserved. \\u00a9 2026 Associated Newspapers Limited.\"}"